subSubSection.paragraph:
Male terminalia; 
Figs. 12–14
. Rather small for such a large species. In lateral view epandrium rather rectangular, one and a half times as wide as high, rather square ventrally and without any significant anterior process, along posterior margin and ventrally with several rows of moderately long setulae all of a rather similar length. Cerci rather small and only slightly protruding from shell of epandrium, bearing multiple rows of setulae along posterior and ventral margins. Surstyli projecting anteriorly as a pointed triangular process. In ventral view surstyli with a row of regularly spaced setulae along their ventral margins, a group of more isolated ones anteriorly. Aedeagus a stout open U-shape, slightly recurved apically, ventrally at base with a swollen area which bears a number of small spicules.
